## Limitations

{% for limitation in limitations -%}
- {{ limitation }}
{% endfor %}
- No final heat loss calculation, cooling-load calculation, ventilation calculation, or humidity analysis is included.
- All heat pump capacity, emitter sizing, UFH loop spacing, pump selection, pipe sizing, duct sizing, and controls values are placeholders until mechanical engineering review.
- Fireplace output, chimney/flue design, combustion air, CO protection, and fire-safety interfaces require specialist review.
- This document must not be used as an installation drawing, energy-code compliance statement, commissioning certificate, or final equipment schedule.

## 1. Heating and Cooling Concept

- Use a low-temperature heating concept based on an air-to-water heat pump, hydronic underfloor heating where configured, and fireplace support in the main living/fireplace zone.
- Cooling is treated as an optional comfort concept only; no final cooling-load calculation or chilled-floor/air-conditioning design is included.
- Final design must coordinate envelope performance, glazing, shading, air tightness, thermal bridges, occupancy, internal gains, and mountain climate exposure.

## 2. Mountain Climate Assumptions

- Site climate: {{ site.climate_zone }}.
- Altitude placeholder: {{ site.altitude_m }} m.
- Frost depth placeholder: {{ site.frost_depth_placeholder_cm }} cm.
- Mountain conditions raise risks around cold starts, snow-blocked outdoor units, defrost drainage, power outages, wind exposure, condensation, and vacant-period freeze protection.

## 3. Air-to-Water Heat Pump Concept

- Heat pump is assumed as the primary heat source for underfloor heating and domestic hot water integration.
- Final capacity, COP/SCOP, design outdoor temperature, bivalent point, backup heat, defrost strategy, noise, refrigerant constraints, and outdoor-unit placement are TBD.
- Outdoor equipment must be protected from snow burial, roof sliding snow, ice, poor drainage, and blocked service access.

## 4. Underfloor Heating Concept

- Underfloor heating is assumed for most occupied areas where room YAML indicates underfloor heating.
- Loop spacing, circuit lengths, manifold count, water temperature, flow rate, screed/floor build-up, controls, and balancing are placeholders.
- Floor finishes must be coordinated with thermal resistance, movement joints, waterproofing, and manufacturer requirements.

